out that the agencies are not primarily to blame and that regulatory failure actually stems from a host of overlooked causes. Steinzor and Shapiro discover that unrelenting funding cuts, a breakdown of the legislative process, an increase in the number of political appointees, a concurrent loss of experienced personnel, chaotic White House oversight, and ceaseless political attacks on the bureaucracy all have contributed to the broken system. But while the news is troubling, the authors also propose a host of reforms, including a new model for measuring the success of the agencies and a revitalization of the civil service. The People’s Agents and the Battle to Protect the American Public is an urgent and compelling appeal to renew America’s best traditions of public service.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAdministrative agencieszUnited States. 0aGovernment accountabilityzUnited States. 0aPublic interestzUnited States. 0aPublic safetyzUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  agovernment, politics, political, health, public, safety, environment, environmentalist, environmental, climate change, america, american, united states, usa, academic, scholarly, research, professor, college, higher education, federal, dangerous, protection, pollution, natural resources, nature, regulation, regulatory, legislation, legislative, white house, bureaucracy, systemic.1 aShapiro, Sidney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022677202840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226772042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226772042/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_